<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:402px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Islm.svg" class="image" title="The IS curve moves to the right, causing higher interest rates (i) and expansion in the &quot;real&quot; economy (real GDP, or Y)."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/Islm.svg/400px-Islm.svg.png" width="400" height="400" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">The <b>IS</b> curve moves to the right, causing higher interest rates (i) and expansion in the "real" economy (real GDP, or Y).</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The <b>IS/LM model</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Macroeconomic" title="Macroeconomic" class="mw-redirect">macroeconomic</a> tool that demonstrates the relationship between interest rates and real output in the goods and services market and the money market. The intersection of the IS and LM curves is the "General Equilibrium" where there is simultaneous equilibrium in all the markets of the economy<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>. IS/LM stands for Investment Saving / Liquidity preference Money supply.</p>
